WEBVTT

00:02.313 --> 00:03.692
How great is this?

00:03.693 --> 00:06.352
Fresh air and the endorphins.

00:06.353 --> 00:10.102
Ooh, and the cute
little babies and dogs.

00:10.103 --> 00:12.062
This puts everything in perspective.

00:12.063 --> 00:13.312
I ought to do this every day.

00:13.313 --> 00:14.732
I swear, I don't know why I don't.

00:14.733 --> 00:16.352
(breathing hard): I need to stop.

00:16.353 --> 00:18.333
We <i>just</i> started.

00:19.603 --> 00:22.102
Gordon hates running.

00:22.103 --> 00:24.402
Then why did Gordon
say "yes" to running?

00:24.403 --> 00:25.802
Because he's insanely competitive?

00:25.803 --> 00:26.802
What are you looking at?

00:26.803 --> 00:27.772
(children laugh)

00:27.773 --> 00:31.732
And yet, here you are,
wallowing in defeat.

00:31.733 --> 00:33.482
This is a hard thing for me to watch.

00:33.483 --> 00:35.232
You'll get over it.

00:35.233 --> 00:36.562
And I sense you need to
talk to me about something

00:36.563 --> 00:38.102
that requires a working brain,

00:38.103 --> 00:39.812
so I'd rather not risk a stroke.

00:39.813 --> 00:42.352
Well, at least walk
with me, you big baby.

00:42.353 --> 00:45.602
Strangely turned on by you abusing me.

00:45.603 --> 00:46.503
This is sensitive.

00:50.143 --> 00:53.102
Something I haven't read my staff in on.

00:53.103 --> 00:55.102
MIKE: Okay.

00:55.103 --> 00:57.232
I'm starting to normalize, go.

00:57.233 --> 01:00.272
Last time I saw Foreign
Minister Avdonin,

01:00.273 --> 01:01.642
he proposed a trade with me.

01:01.643 --> 01:02.623
Do I need context?

01:02.624 --> 01:03.692
No.

01:03.693 --> 01:07.142
Peter Buckley for an American asset

01:07.143 --> 01:10.602
with a great deal of personal
significance to Henry and me.

01:10.603 --> 01:12.562
Previously, they told us he was dead.

01:12.563 --> 01:14.746
Now they're saying he's not,
and we could get him back.

01:14.747 --> 01:19.942
Now, I know the politics of
a trade can be complicated,

01:19.943 --> 01:22.522
so I'm asking if you
could imagine a scenario

01:22.523 --> 01:25.482
where Dalton might agree to that deal.

01:25.483 --> 01:26.692
No. Breakfast?

01:26.693 --> 01:29.312
Come on.

01:29.313 --> 01:31.296
You're really gonna make
me step this out for you?

01:31.297 --> 01:33.812
First, to clarify, Peter Buckley,

01:33.813 --> 01:35.762
the most notorious
American spy in history.

01:35.763 --> 01:37.482
- Responsible for the deaths
- I know that.

01:37.483 --> 01:38.732
of six CIA agents,

01:38.733 --> 01:39.942
Two of whom, Dalton,

01:39.943 --> 01:42.272
former Director of the
CIA, knew personally.

01:42.273 --> 01:43.852
That Peter Buckley? I'm sorry,

01:43.853 --> 01:44.942
I actually do need context

01:44.943 --> 01:46.852
as to why you would ask
me anything so stupid.

01:46.853 --> 01:49.352
Because it is incredibly important,

01:49.353 --> 01:50.812
and there's a clock on it.

01:50.813 --> 01:52.482
You really made me step <i>that</i> out?

01:52.483 --> 01:54.642
Okay. Even if Dalton would consider it,

01:54.643 --> 01:57.042
Russell Jackson would throw
his body in front of that train.

01:57.043 --> 01:58.026
Making a trade like that

01:58.027 --> 01:59.610
with the Russians, in an election year?

01:59.611 --> 02:01.812
Even if you had monkey
pictures on both of them,

02:01.813 --> 02:03.522
- and got them to agree,
- What are monkey pictures?

02:03.523 --> 02:05.786
I highly doubt your prisoner
exchange is even legitimate.

02:05.787 --> 02:08.312
If you think your asset is
dead, he's probably dead.

02:08.312 --> 02:09.482
But by even

02:09.483 --> 02:11.482
considering a trade for Buckley,

02:11.483 --> 02:13.562
you've revealed your
attachment to your asset.

02:13.563 --> 02:15.482
Now, Avdonin's using
that to his advantage,

02:15.483 --> 02:17.312
claiming this dead person is alive

02:17.313 --> 02:18.776
without having to provide any proof.

02:18.777 --> 02:20.562
So brilliant negotiating strategy there.

02:20.563 --> 02:22.442
I he... I hear you,

02:22.443 --> 02:25.413
when you say you think
this is a terrible idea.

02:27.353 --> 02:29.312
But I haven't had a moment's peace

02:29.313 --> 02:31.352
since I realized this was possible.

02:31.353 --> 02:33.602
I have to try.

02:33.603 --> 02:36.522
Can't... can't you just do your thing...

02:36.523 --> 02:39.522
to find out exactly how
suicidal this mission is?

02:39.523 --> 02:40.666
I guess I could talk to some

02:40.667 --> 02:42.022
of my data-wonk pollster friends,

02:42.023 --> 02:43.522
and see what the favorability stats

02:43.523 --> 02:44.982
would be on a Buckley trade.

02:44.983 --> 02:46.902
And it has been almost 20 years

02:46.903 --> 02:48.522
and people are idiots.

02:48.523 --> 02:50.106
Long-term memory is at an all-time low,

02:50.107 --> 02:51.522
so we've got that going for us.

02:51.523 --> 02:52.852
Well, see?

02:52.853 --> 02:54.953
Things are looking up already.

02:55.733 --> 02:57.232
(sighs deeply)

02:57.233 --> 02:57.963
HENRY: Hey, babe.

02:57.964 --> 02:58.732
Hey.

02:58.733 --> 02:59.942
Hey, Mom. How was your run?

02:59.943 --> 03:02.402
It was great. I feel so clean

03:02.403 --> 03:04.522
and healthy and... (gasps). Waffles!?

03:04.523 --> 03:05.826
Yeah, Dad fixed the waffle iron.

03:05.827 --> 03:06.692
Yes!

03:06.693 --> 03:07.836
It just needed a new switch.

03:07.837 --> 03:09.642
And he built a firepit in the backyard.

03:09.643 --> 03:11.982
- I dug a hole and put some bricks
around it. - ELIZABETH (laughs): What?

03:11.983 --> 03:13.531
Course, the Secret Service
won't let us use it.

03:13.532 --> 03:14.127
ELIZABETH: Aw...

03:14.128 --> 03:16.272
ALISON: And now he's talking mini-golf.

03:16.273 --> 03:19.732
Ho! So this is Henry
McCord on sabbatical, huh?

03:19.733 --> 03:20.942
I'm enjoying the time.

03:20.943 --> 03:22.562
It doesn't happen that often.

03:22.563 --> 03:24.602
And come on, we love mini-golf.

03:24.603 --> 03:26.186
It was a Friday night thing for like...

03:26.187 --> 03:26.852
A summer.

03:26.853 --> 03:28.402
Two summers, at least.

03:28.403 --> 03:29.301
You sure have been jazzed

03:29.302 --> 03:30.902
about all these
life-affirming activities

03:30.903 --> 03:32.401
since your weekend with a think tank

03:32.402 --> 03:34.104
- in San Diego.
- I've got the time off.

03:34.105 --> 03:35.649
I think I should take advantage of it.

03:35.650 --> 03:36.402
So, come on,

03:36.403 --> 03:38.163
who's in? Mini-golf tonight.

03:39.103 --> 03:40.142
Um, I can't.

03:40.143 --> 03:41.968
I have to see Jareth tonight.

03:41.969 --> 03:44.267
'Cause he just accepted a...

03:44.268 --> 03:45.517
two-year fellowship in Oxford,

03:45.518 --> 03:47.622
so we have to talk about
how we're going to do the...

03:47.623 --> 03:48.141
(sighs)

03:48.142 --> 03:48.966
long-distance thing.

03:48.967 --> 03:50.017
ELIZABETH: Gosh,

03:50.018 --> 03:52.057
honey, that... that's
rough, but you know what?

03:52.058 --> 03:52.961
Your dad and I did it.

03:52.962 --> 03:53.848
A lot of people do it.

03:53.849 --> 03:54.807
ELIZABETH: Yeah.

03:54.808 --> 03:55.897
You'll-you'll figure it out.

03:55.898 --> 03:57.380
- Hey, uh, you know what would really
clear your minds, - STEVIE: Dad.

03:57.381 --> 03:59.644
- Give you some perspective...
Mini-golf. - Don't... Dad.

03:59.645 --> 04:01.017
I'm serious. Just ask Jareth.

04:01.018 --> 04:02.727
He's British. He's got to like golf.

04:02.728 --> 04:03.387
Mini-golf.

04:03.388 --> 04:04.887
Hey, help me out.

04:04.888 --> 04:05.723
Alison, Jason.

04:05.724 --> 04:07.428
- All right. Fine. I'm in.
- Yeah, me, too.

04:07.429 --> 04:08.347
I'll ask him.

04:08.348 --> 04:09.727
Joe and Mimma's after

04:09.728 --> 04:11.407
- for gooey calzones, yeah?
- They bought.

04:11.408 --> 04:12.307
Stop selling.

04:12.308 --> 04:14.307
Well, they'll get into
it once we're there.

04:14.308 --> 04:15.948
I'm sure.

04:16.468 --> 04:20.846
So aside from fixing the waffle iron,

04:20.848 --> 04:22.597
and building a firepit,

04:22.598 --> 04:24.427
and obsessing about mini-golf,

04:24.428 --> 04:26.637
everything okay post Islamabad?

04:26.638 --> 04:28.427
It's fine.

04:28.428 --> 04:30.807
'Cause, you know, we
could always go back

04:30.808 --> 04:32.637
and see Dr. Sherman.

04:32.638 --> 04:34.597
Honestly, I just want to immerse myself

04:34.598 --> 04:36.677
in mindless activities for a while.

04:36.678 --> 04:37.948
Okay.

04:39.468 --> 04:41.427
Not counting on me
for mini-golf, are you?

04:41.428 --> 04:44.395
Uh, after the last time, I don't think
you're allowed back there,

04:44.396 --> 04:46.011
- 'cause you threw...
- I did not throw that club.

04:46.012 --> 04:46.698
All... all right.

04:46.699 --> 04:47.517
I...I...

04:47.518 --> 04:49.189
- ...was gesturing.
- Yeah, tell that

04:49.190 --> 04:51.533
- and it slipped. My hands were wet.
- to the lady who's...

04:51.534 --> 04:53.764
- We'll miss you.
- I think it was raining.

04:53.899 --> 04:55.028
JAY: <i>Our intel is that</i>

04:55.029 --> 04:57.608
all remnants of Hizb Al-Shahid
have gone underground.

04:57.609 --> 04:59.568
Even the remaining stolen uranium

04:59.569 --> 05:01.568
has been found and
seized by American forces.

05:01.569 --> 05:02.632
Yeah, their press releases

05:02.633 --> 05:05.818
are all full of optimism,
and national pride.

05:05.819 --> 05:08.188
Global response has been positive,

05:08.189 --> 05:09.818
with just a handful
of the usual suspects

05:09.819 --> 05:11.122
grumbling about U.S. aggression.

05:11.123 --> 05:14.528
From a polling data and optics
perspective, we're on course.

05:14.529 --> 05:16.858
Okay. Good. Um,

05:16.859 --> 05:18.608
No Matt, today?

05:18.609 --> 05:20.032
Commencement season. He's holed up.

05:20.033 --> 05:23.528
Apparently, he's agreed to
write six speeches this year.

05:23.529 --> 05:25.278
Yeah, including mine.

05:25.279 --> 05:27.608
Oh, who are the lucky graduates?

05:27.609 --> 05:28.709
UMASS Pittsfield.

05:30.529 --> 05:32.648
(clears throat) They have quite a
respected foreign policy program.

05:32.649 --> 05:33.512
And they asked first.

05:33.513 --> 05:35.408
The Secretary's a big
fan of "asked first."

05:35.409 --> 05:37.818
- (chair squeaking)
- Was that Dr. McCord's strategy, ma'am?

05:37.819 --> 05:40.238
(laughs) Possibly.

05:40.239 --> 05:41.579
I have an appointment.

05:42.529 --> 05:44.478
It's personal. Spontaneous.

05:44.479 --> 05:45.528
Whimsical, even.

05:45.529 --> 05:47.629
It's fine. I'm reachable.

05:50.819 --> 05:52.339
I know what that is.

05:53.279 --> 05:53.924
Madam Secretary.

05:53.925 --> 05:54.648
Yeah.

05:54.649 --> 05:55.608
Oh, you're leaving?

05:55.609 --> 05:56.818
I'll be back.

05:56.819 --> 05:58.028
I was working on your
commencement speech,

05:58.029 --> 05:59.738
and I was hoping you could give me

05:59.739 --> 06:00.898
some personal anecdote

06:00.899 --> 06:03.318
that-that proffers
some nugget of wisdom

06:03.319 --> 06:04.528
that we could give the kids.

06:04.529 --> 06:07.648
Uh, saving the Pacific Rim
Trade Agreement, for example.

06:07.649 --> 06:09.358
Détente with Russia.

06:09.359 --> 06:10.622
Dropping the embargo with Cuba.

06:10.623 --> 06:12.278
I mean, there's a lot of good options.

06:12.279 --> 06:13.782
Yeah, I-I-I don't know if any of that

06:13.783 --> 06:15.978
really jibes with my overall message.

06:15.979 --> 06:17.648
You have an overall message?

06:17.649 --> 06:20.478
I don't know. Do I?

06:20.479 --> 06:22.568
I'm just data-gathering,
but I'm open to your ideas.

06:22.569 --> 06:24.858
I... let me... let me mull it over.

06:24.859 --> 06:27.068
See if I can come up with a message,

06:27.069 --> 06:28.818
or even a theme.

06:28.819 --> 06:30.898
Ooh, a theme would be awesome.

06:30.899 --> 06:33.278
Oh, what about the chrysalis thing?

06:33.279 --> 06:35.648
A caterpillar into the butterfly...?

06:35.649 --> 06:38.028
Are you messing with me?

06:38.029 --> 06:40.738
(bell tolling slowly)

06:40.739 --> 06:42.778
ELIZABETH: Anton, thank you for agreeing

06:42.779 --> 06:45.478
to meet on short notice.

06:45.479 --> 06:47.648
ANTON: The last time we
did this, it worked out.

06:47.649 --> 06:49.608
ELIZABETH: It did. Those boys

06:49.609 --> 06:52.398
made it safely home
from Syria. Thank you.

06:52.399 --> 06:56.398
You're still a cultural attaché, huh?

06:56.399 --> 06:57.528
Yes.

06:57.529 --> 06:59.108
The work itself is quite dull,

06:59.109 --> 07:02.568
but the quality of life
makes it all worthwhile.

07:02.569 --> 07:06.778
Katarina got into Harvard, early action.

07:06.779 --> 07:08.539
Congratulations.

07:09.819 --> 07:11.478
I need information

07:11.479 --> 07:14.898
on a Russian army
captain, Dmitri Petrov.

07:14.899 --> 07:17.648
Officially, he died from a fever

07:17.649 --> 07:19.608
he contracted while stationed in Ukraine

07:19.609 --> 07:20.524
during the conflict.

07:20.525 --> 07:21.478
Yes.

07:21.479 --> 07:23.818
Officially, that is how
every Russian soldier

07:23.819 --> 07:26.688
who died at the front met his fate.

07:26.689 --> 07:28.858
Our young men are impervious to bullets,

07:28.859 --> 07:31.608
but, sadly, suffer from weak lungs.

07:31.609 --> 07:33.738
I have reason to
believe he's still alive,

07:33.739 --> 07:35.858
but I need hard evidence.
Incontrovertible.

07:35.859 --> 07:37.528
And why do you care so much

07:37.529 --> 07:39.499
about this particular
Russian army captain?

07:41.689 --> 07:43.648
I know you do realize that I'm friends

07:43.649 --> 07:45.192
with the dean of admission at Harvard.

07:45.193 --> 07:49.778
I'm sure Katarina got
in on her own merits,

07:49.779 --> 07:51.818
but you did list me as a reference,

07:51.819 --> 07:56.398
and I had some free
time, and I made a call.

07:56.399 --> 08:00.039
I will do my best, Madam Secretary.

08:01.979 --> 08:03.499
Thank you.

08:10.899 --> 08:12.642
(music playing, golf
ball plinking into cup)

08:12.643 --> 08:14.421
HENRY: Have anything like
this in the UK, Jareth?

08:14.422 --> 08:15.631
JARETH (chuckles): No, sir.

08:15.632 --> 08:17.272
Golf's quite a serious
pursuit over there.

08:17.273 --> 08:19.102
STEVIE: It's fine to think it's goofy.

08:19.103 --> 08:20.442
Part of its charm.

08:25.962 --> 08:27.791
Your turn, dingus. Go.

08:27.792 --> 08:29.591
Um, I'll pass on this one.

08:29.592 --> 08:30.815
I know those guys from school.

08:30.816 --> 08:32.001
But what about your score?

08:32.001 --> 08:32.818
What was...?

08:32.820 --> 08:35.211
It's already the size
of the national debt.

08:35.212 --> 08:36.551
Let her go.

08:36.552 --> 08:39.841
Hello, hole-in-one.

08:39.842 --> 08:40.852
HENRY: Oh, sorry.

08:47.882 --> 08:49.631
You know what? This is ridiculous.

08:49.632 --> 08:50.841
The clowns and the windmills

08:50.842 --> 08:51.825
and the jumping dolphins

08:51.826 --> 08:53.291
are supposed to convey an atmosphere

08:53.292 --> 08:54.771
of family fun, while the game itself

08:54.772 --> 08:56.155
is just designed to infuriate you.

08:56.156 --> 08:58.381
Okay, look, just take a
deep breath. It's okay.

08:58.382 --> 08:59.527
It's all right.

08:59.528 --> 09:00.772
I'm getting a snow cone.

09:02.052 --> 09:03.671
I counsel we skip this one.

09:03.672 --> 09:05.482
Just give ourselves twos and move on.

09:08.552 --> 09:10.501
Sorry, this isn't exactly the
kind of outing I'd planned.

09:10.502 --> 09:11.501
No, it's fine. I'm having a lovely time.

09:11.502 --> 09:13.251
Um, wh-while... while
I've got you a moment,

09:13.252 --> 09:15.155
- there's something I wanted to ask you.
- Sure.

09:15.156 --> 09:16.711
Um, I know Stevie's already told you

09:16.712 --> 09:18.671
that I accepted a fellowship at Oxford.

09:18.672 --> 09:21.051
Yes. Oh, wow, I-I know
you're going to work

09:21.052 --> 09:22.711
- the relationship part out.
- Yeah.

09:22.712 --> 09:24.655
Elizabeth and I did it
when I was in the Marines,

09:24.656 --> 09:26.679
and that was before Skype
and JetBlue and all that.

09:26.680 --> 09:29.631
Yeah. Oh, oh, see, uh,
uh, about that, um...

09:29.632 --> 09:31.522
see, the thing is, Dr. McCord, um...

09:33.552 --> 09:36.751
The thing is, I'm hopelessly
in love with your daughter.

09:36.752 --> 09:39.631
And I don't... I don't want to imagine

09:39.632 --> 09:42.751
my life without her. I...

09:42.752 --> 09:46.751
I don't want to go off to
Oxford without this settled,

09:46.752 --> 09:52.091
um, and so, I suppose,
I'm rather awkwardly, uh,

09:52.092 --> 09:55.812
asking your blessing to propose to her.

09:59.422 --> 10:00.591
Propose...

10:00.592 --> 10:02.072
Marriage?

10:02.073 --> 10:03.631
That's what I said.

10:03.632 --> 10:05.791
I mean, don't these kids
have other steps, first?

10:05.792 --> 10:06.627
The way we did.

10:06.628 --> 10:07.461
I know.

10:07.462 --> 10:09.631
Like... living together.

10:09.632 --> 10:10.461
Breaking up,

10:10.462 --> 10:11.547
and living together.

10:11.548 --> 10:12.631
We didn't break up.

10:12.632 --> 10:14.751
I-I just needed a
little time to freak out.

10:14.752 --> 10:15.961
It was the worst

10:15.962 --> 10:17.501
- five days of my life.
- Three.

10:17.502 --> 10:20.341
Followed by the greatest proposal ever.

10:20.342 --> 10:23.751
Yes, the discount skywriter.

10:23.752 --> 10:25.711
"Mar Me Elibet."

10:25.712 --> 10:26.921
Hey, it worked.

10:26.922 --> 10:28.791
It did. But wait...

10:28.792 --> 10:30.812
So what did you say?

10:31.712 --> 10:32.982
I said yes.

10:34.792 --> 10:36.062
Without talking to me?

10:37.592 --> 10:38.591
Wow!

10:38.592 --> 10:43.381
Did you guys just
full-on Edith Wharton this

10:43.382 --> 10:45.961
and act like my voice
wasn't going to matter?

10:45.962 --> 10:48.812
Did you negotiate a dowry?

10:49.842 --> 10:51.671
I-I... honestly,
babe, I was so stunned,

10:51.672 --> 10:53.841
I might have actually
turned into an idiot.

10:53.842 --> 10:55.711
- Huh.
- It was really more E.M. Forster

10:55.712 --> 10:57.501
'cause of the whole English thing.

10:57.502 --> 11:00.001
Look, it was just...

11:00.002 --> 11:02.551
It's just a formality, anyway.

11:02.552 --> 11:04.751
He's going to do what he wants.

11:04.752 --> 11:07.501
Well, what do we say if she says yes?

11:07.502 --> 11:08.461
I don't know.

11:08.462 --> 11:12.671
He's such a great guy,
but they're so young.

11:12.672 --> 11:15.501
That's what we say.

11:15.502 --> 11:18.501
We love Jareth,

11:18.502 --> 11:21.631
but we will love him
even more in two years.

11:21.632 --> 11:24.091
Okay, let's just see what happens.

11:24.092 --> 11:26.051
It's just getting engaged.

11:26.052 --> 11:27.591
Exactly, exactly.

11:27.592 --> 11:29.591
And they can take their
time getting married.

11:29.592 --> 11:33.711
I mean, some-some...
engagements go on forever.

11:33.712 --> 11:36.591
My brother and Sophie?

11:36.592 --> 11:38.711
(scoffs) Oh, yeah,
like, 15 years, right?

11:38.712 --> 11:40.615
- (laughing): Yeah.
- Did they ever get married?

11:40.616 --> 11:42.501
I don't know. I think so.

11:42.502 --> 11:44.501
(sighs) You know what,

11:44.502 --> 11:47.841
this... is kind of a champagne problem.

11:47.842 --> 11:52.501
I mean, this terrific guy with
a fellowship to Oxford in physics

11:52.502 --> 11:54.961
wants to marry our daughter.

11:54.962 --> 11:56.501
I think we'll survive.

11:56.502 --> 11:57.192
(laughing): Yeah.

11:57.193 --> 11:57.982
(chuckles)

12:02.882 --> 12:04.881
Oh, Henry.

12:04.882 --> 12:06.852
Our baby.

12:11.462 --> 12:13.562
I know.

12:15.748 --> 12:17.251
JAY: <i>After your commencement address,</i>

12:17.252 --> 12:19.751
you'll be joining the school's president

12:19.752 --> 12:20.921
for a luncheon in his home.

12:20.922 --> 12:23.131
(gasps) Gordon, come here, good buddy.

12:23.132 --> 12:24.501
Come here, come on, Gordon.

12:24.502 --> 12:25.591
There's a good boy.

12:25.592 --> 12:27.591
Mike B., you can come in.

12:27.592 --> 12:28.551
Hi.

12:28.552 --> 12:30.751
Are we doing this
here, in front of them?

12:30.752 --> 12:34.211
Always a pleasure to see you too, Mike.

12:34.212 --> 12:36.635
I'm ready to read them in. Here,
you go walk with Uncle Mike.

12:36.636 --> 12:38.946
Oh, come here. All
right. Who raised you?

12:39.712 --> 12:40.751
ELIZABETH: So, uh,

12:40.752 --> 12:44.091
had Mike B. running
some favorability numbers

12:44.092 --> 12:47.841
on the idea of trading Peter
Buckley to the Russians.

12:47.842 --> 12:49.835
Obviously, that does
not leave this room.

12:49.836 --> 12:50.746
Well, it ain't pretty.

12:50.747 --> 12:53.349
48% say they'd view
the trade unfavorably.

12:53.350 --> 12:55.018
Well, that's less than 50.

12:55.019 --> 12:58.058
With 32% saying they'd view
it "extremely unfavorably."

12:58.059 --> 12:59.218
Oh.

12:59.219 --> 13:00.842
And how would they view President Dalton

13:00.843 --> 13:01.978
for making such a trade?

13:01.979 --> 13:05.348
Ah, that came in at 78%:
"What are you, nuts?"

13:05.349 --> 13:07.018
Figured as much.

13:07.019 --> 13:08.218
That's why you're here.

13:08.219 --> 13:10.058
Wha...?

13:10.059 --> 13:11.558
I have no idea what's going on.

13:11.559 --> 13:13.218
It's Washington. Who does?

13:13.219 --> 13:15.388
I want you to put together a package

13:15.389 --> 13:18.178
of inducements of equal or greater value

13:18.179 --> 13:19.522
to the Russians as Peter Buckley.

13:19.523 --> 13:20.348
Can you do that?

13:20.349 --> 13:23.598
I can try, but it'll have
to be pretty damn enticing.

13:23.599 --> 13:25.178
He's kind of a white whale for them.

13:25.179 --> 13:27.978
And who or what would we be

13:27.979 --> 13:29.138
getting in return?

13:29.139 --> 13:32.348
Let's just say another white whale.

13:32.349 --> 13:34.333
Understood, ma'am.

13:34.334 --> 13:36.414
Great, now that we're done
speaking in Melville code,

13:36.415 --> 13:37.262
can we have the room?

13:37.263 --> 13:41.072
You and I have other
problems to discuss.

13:47.013 --> 13:48.012
Really?

13:48.013 --> 13:49.642
Really.

13:49.643 --> 13:51.012
Really.

13:51.013 --> 13:52.642
Fine.

13:52.643 --> 13:54.866
My friend also told me that
his company was commissioned

13:54.867 --> 13:57.227
by an unnamed entity...
read: the White House...

13:57.228 --> 13:59.637
to do a poll on three
people: Albert Kopp,

13:59.638 --> 14:02.597
Lloyd Frost and Calvin Hastings.

14:02.598 --> 14:03.643
So?

14:03.644 --> 14:04.727
They're all heavy-hitters

14:04.728 --> 14:06.597
with foreign policy credentials.

14:06.598 --> 14:08.427
In fact, they were on the short list

14:08.428 --> 14:10.051
- (snoring)
- after Secretary Marsh died.

14:10.052 --> 14:11.712
The White House is looking to dump you.

14:12.928 --> 14:14.927
(laughing): Oh, come on.

14:14.928 --> 14:16.578
What...?

14:19.688 --> 14:22.727
First of all, Conrad is a friend.

14:22.728 --> 14:24.448
Uh-huh.

14:25.518 --> 14:27.347
And secondly,

14:27.348 --> 14:29.427
I-I-I've had a few successes.

14:29.428 --> 14:31.427
Listen, you could be Thomas Jefferson,

14:31.428 --> 14:33.891
but I'm telling you, it looks
like you're about to get canned.

14:33.892 --> 14:35.517
Why?

14:35.518 --> 14:36.477
It's an election year.

14:36.478 --> 14:38.698
There... there could
be a million reasons.

14:42.978 --> 14:44.977
Well, thank you for the
heads up, Mike, but...

14:44.978 --> 14:47.807
I'm not worried.

14:47.808 --> 14:50.477
And now that that's settled,

14:50.478 --> 14:52.807
let's let the secretary
get back to work.

14:52.808 --> 14:54.578
Sure. Why not?

15:00.848 --> 15:02.948
♪ ♪

15:03.179 --> 15:08.182
