20:16.401 --> 20:17.740
BLAKE: <i>Uh, good morning, ma'am.</i>

20:17.741 --> 20:18.740
<i>Uh, you received a call</i>

20:18.741 --> 20:19.820
from an Anton Durchenko

20:19.821 --> 20:21.490
from the Russian Embassy.

20:21.491 --> 20:22.490
- Yeah.
- Uh...

20:22.491 --> 20:23.870
He's a cultural attaché.

20:23.871 --> 20:25.174
He-he-he says that you know him.

20:25.175 --> 20:26.910
Yeah, from my CIA days.

20:26.911 --> 20:29.160
Oh, well, uh, he called to
invite you to a concert today

20:29.161 --> 20:30.910
at the Russian Embassy.

20:30.911 --> 20:33.240
I told him you were very
busy but he insisted that

20:33.241 --> 20:34.780
you would be interested.

20:34.781 --> 20:37.280
It's, uh, <i>Rachmaninoff's
String Quartet Number 1.</i>

20:37.281 --> 20:38.881
Okay, clear my afternoon.

20:39.951 --> 20:40.740
R-Really?

20:40.741 --> 20:43.490
Yeah, I could use a little break.

20:43.491 --> 20:45.080
Tell Anton I'm coming.

20:45.081 --> 20:47.160
Uh, yes, ma'am.

20:47.161 --> 20:49.620
Bring you back some caviar and vodka.

20:49.621 --> 20:50.780
Oh, please, don't.

20:50.781 --> 20:52.881
I'm cleansing.

20:53.821 --> 20:55.921
<i>(Rachmaninoff's String
Quartet Number 1 plays)</i>

21:21.821 --> 21:23.921
That's all the
documentation I could find.

21:25.201 --> 21:27.301
<i>(String Quartet Number
1 continues playing)</i>

21:53.531 --> 21:56.761
(sighs)

21:58.621 --> 21:59.820
ELIZABETH: <i>Minister Avdonin,</i>

21:59.821 --> 22:01.910
where did you think this road would lead

22:01.911 --> 22:05.030
when you decided to manipulate me

22:05.031 --> 22:06.660
and the United States Government?

22:06.661 --> 22:08.990
It took exactly one move from me

22:08.991 --> 22:11.030
to find the proof that Captain Dmitri

22:11.031 --> 22:12.080
Petrov is dead.

22:12.081 --> 22:13.950
Madam Secretary, forgive me,

22:13.951 --> 22:16.370
but I have to call into
question this so-called proof

22:16.371 --> 22:17.820
that you claim to have.

22:17.821 --> 22:19.660
Oh, it was-it was pretty convincing.

22:19.661 --> 22:21.030
Dmitri Petrov's treachery

22:21.031 --> 22:23.200
had to remain secret to the public

22:23.201 --> 22:26.200
at large, but in order
to maintain the appearance

22:26.201 --> 22:28.700
of strength among the
military's officer class,

22:28.701 --> 22:32.870
President Salnikov falsified
the captain's execution.

22:32.871 --> 22:36.740
I saw a photo of him
with a bullet in his head.

22:36.741 --> 22:38.080
What can I say?

22:38.081 --> 22:39.921
We're very good at what we do.

22:41.081 --> 22:44.080
I want proof of life
before we can proceed.

22:44.081 --> 22:45.410
No.

22:45.411 --> 22:47.740
President Salnikov wants to maintain

22:47.741 --> 22:49.370
the pretense of Dmitri's death.

22:49.371 --> 22:52.780
He will not risk exposing this operation

22:52.781 --> 22:55.910
for anything short of
Peter Buckley's freedom.

22:55.911 --> 22:58.740
It's the reason why he
kept the traitor alive.

22:58.741 --> 23:00.910
Now he sees that the time is right,

23:00.911 --> 23:03.240
given such high-level interest.

23:03.241 --> 23:06.740
I would only consider
moving forward with the trade

23:06.741 --> 23:10.261
if there was a good faith gesture.

23:11.911 --> 23:14.950
Dmitri Petrov's sister Talia released

23:14.951 --> 23:17.080
from prison in advance.

23:17.081 --> 23:19.660
That can be arranged.

23:19.661 --> 23:22.120
I will process the orders right away.

23:22.121 --> 23:25.120
But as for Dmitri,
it's Buckley or nothing.

23:25.121 --> 23:27.120
And I'm running out of patience.

23:27.121 --> 23:30.051
Good-bye, Madam Secretary.

23:31.871 --> 23:32.910
Ma'am, a word?

23:32.911 --> 23:33.910
We have proof.

23:33.911 --> 23:34.854
You're on your way out.

23:34.855 --> 23:36.450
We have some rather unsettling news,

23:36.451 --> 23:37.611
but I wouldn't call it proof.

23:37.612 --> 23:39.146
They're gonna be moving the
furniture out while you're

23:39.147 --> 23:40.910
- protecting her feelings.
- Just tell me.

23:40.911 --> 23:42.780
Calvin Hastings' wife
moved heaven and earth

23:42.781 --> 23:44.284
to get their child put on a wait list

23:44.285 --> 23:45.950
for the Circle of Friends preschool,

23:45.951 --> 23:47.254
which is the finger paint feeder

23:47.255 --> 23:48.910
for all the best prep schools in DC.

23:48.911 --> 23:51.120
Hastings doesn't even have
a preschool-aged child.

23:51.121 --> 23:52.780
He will soon enough.

23:52.781 --> 23:55.091
His wife is six months pregnant.

23:58.991 --> 24:01.091
Damn it.

24:04.760 --> 24:06.160
Hey. I was just coming to find you.

24:06.161 --> 24:07.666
I have a draft. It's rough,

24:07.667 --> 24:09.823
- but I think it's pretty good.
- (sighs) The commencement speech.

24:09.824 --> 24:10.551
I-I can't.

24:10.552 --> 24:11.320
You can't what?

24:11.321 --> 24:13.990
I-I can't do it.
There's a lot going on.

24:13.991 --> 24:14.952
It's complicated.

24:14.953 --> 24:17.604
Bailing on them at this
point, all due respect,

24:17.605 --> 24:18.817
- is pretty rude.
- I'm not bailing on them.

24:18.818 --> 24:19.543
I'm sending you.

24:19.544 --> 24:20.558
Wait, wait, what?!

24:20.559 --> 24:23.160
Look, you wrote the speech.
It's all you.

24:23.161 --> 24:25.950
And, besides, the kids will
relate to you more. Thank you.

24:25.951 --> 24:27.950
I'll coordinate it. Just trust me.

24:27.951 --> 24:29.990
Madam Secretary, they're
really expecting you.

24:29.991 --> 24:31.870
I'm-I'm gonna be a big disappointment.

24:31.871 --> 24:33.910
Look, I'll make a
contribution to the school.

24:33.911 --> 24:36.080
I'll take individual
meetings with the graduates.

24:36.081 --> 24:37.910
- How many?
- 400.

24:37.911 --> 24:40.530
(sighs) We'll figure it out. And, Matt,

24:40.531 --> 24:42.950
you're not gonna be a disappointment.

24:42.951 --> 24:45.181
You're gonna crush it.

24:51.371 --> 24:52.370
Elise.

24:52.371 --> 24:54.530
Russell...

24:54.531 --> 24:57.530
(chuckling): Now that I'm
on the other side of this,

24:57.531 --> 24:59.120
it is pretty rude.

24:59.121 --> 25:00.370
We need to talk.

25:00.371 --> 25:03.370
Yes, we do.

25:03.371 --> 25:06.200
You need to drop the
Peter Buckley thing.

25:06.201 --> 25:10.080
Look, I have no idea why you'd want

25:10.081 --> 25:12.030
to give up a traitor to the Russians.

25:12.031 --> 25:15.160
All I know is that you have no
business even discussing this

25:15.161 --> 25:16.780
in the middle of an election.

25:16.781 --> 25:20.301
And why should I listen to
this when I'm losing my job?

25:22.161 --> 25:24.160
Yeah.

25:24.161 --> 25:26.820
Two can play at the omniscience game.

25:26.821 --> 25:29.240
I know that you are planning on offering

25:29.241 --> 25:31.820
my position to Calvin Hastings.

25:31.821 --> 25:33.971
(sighs) Look...

25:36.581 --> 25:38.449
I can't talk about this.

25:43.411 --> 25:46.341
You're not even denying it?

25:48.241 --> 25:51.580
You need to talk to the president, soon.

25:51.581 --> 25:54.280
He's in Chicago at a fund-raiser.

25:54.281 --> 25:56.080
He'll be back tomorrow.

25:56.081 --> 25:58.410
I'll get you a face-to-face with him.

25:58.411 --> 26:01.080
Don't bring up Buckley.

26:01.081 --> 26:02.160
We'll see about that.

26:02.161 --> 26:04.011
(door shuts)

26:10.121 --> 26:12.221
(sighs)

26:24.065 --> 26:25.394
HENRY: <i>We love Jareth.</i>

26:25.395 --> 26:27.184
We think he's a great guy.

26:27.185 --> 26:29.415
But you're rushing into
this marriage too quickly.

26:32.065 --> 26:33.014
No, just "rushing."

26:33.015 --> 26:35.564
"Rushing" is "quickly."
You don't need both.

26:35.565 --> 26:38.474
You're rushing into
this marriage. And why?

26:38.475 --> 26:39.814
Marriage is forever,

26:39.815 --> 26:41.758
and forever is a lot
longer than you think it is.

26:41.759 --> 26:43.644
This is stupid.

26:43.645 --> 26:45.474
Okay.

26:45.475 --> 26:48.354
Just go out there and start talking.

26:48.355 --> 26:49.814
It can't be that hard.

26:49.815 --> 26:51.354
STEVIE: <i>Yeah, but isn't an up-do,</i>

26:51.355 --> 26:52.520
like, too much going on?

26:52.521 --> 26:53.724
Not if it's casual,

26:53.725 --> 26:55.394
- like a modified ballerina bun
- Yeah.

26:55.395 --> 26:56.564
or a messy French twist.

26:56.565 --> 26:59.088
Oh, you mean the ones that
messy, like, have to look messy

26:59.089 --> 27:00.799
but you can't actually have
them be mess... (laughs)

27:00.800 --> 27:01.514
That's the magic.

27:01.515 --> 27:02.954
- Thank God you're here.
- Hey, Dad.

27:02.955 --> 27:05.354
Hey. It's just a dry run.

27:05.355 --> 27:07.684
Um, the big day is still on Saturday.

27:07.685 --> 27:09.724
You look beautiful.

27:09.725 --> 27:11.274
Noodle, could we have a minute?

27:11.275 --> 27:13.184
Of course.

27:13.185 --> 27:14.205
Thank you.

27:14.206 --> 27:15.274
(grunts)

27:15.275 --> 27:17.000
You look so beautiful. Seriously.

27:17.001 --> 27:18.825
Thanks, Ali.

27:20.185 --> 27:22.604
So...

27:22.605 --> 27:24.514
is this the big sentimental dad talk

27:24.515 --> 27:26.535
about sending me off into the world?

27:28.605 --> 27:29.705
Not exactly.

27:30.685 --> 27:32.665
Okay.

27:34.605 --> 27:36.814
Look...

27:36.815 --> 27:39.224
Mom and I are concerned that...

27:39.225 --> 27:41.325
It's too soon, isn't it?

27:45.395 --> 27:46.495
Yes.

27:50.395 --> 27:51.825
Oh, God.

27:54.355 --> 27:56.774
I was wondering when one
of you was gonna stop me

27:56.775 --> 27:59.564
from doing something incredibly...

27:59.565 --> 28:01.394
impulsive and stupid,

28:01.395 --> 28:04.394
which this does feel like it is.

28:04.395 --> 28:07.514
But at the same time...

28:07.515 --> 28:10.104
I love him, and...

28:10.105 --> 28:12.564
I don't want to lose him.

28:12.565 --> 28:14.495
And I know that he's the forever guy.

28:15.775 --> 28:18.684
I just don't know that I want
to start forever right now.

28:18.685 --> 28:21.564
Right. Because forever is a
lot longer than you think it is.

28:21.565 --> 28:25.224
I just didn't know what
to say when he proposed.

28:25.225 --> 28:28.564
I mean, people were watching.

28:28.565 --> 28:31.274
And it was so romantic!

28:31.275 --> 28:34.684
And he's the greatest guy... ever.

28:34.685 --> 28:39.455
Being willing to take
that risk, you know?

28:43.435 --> 28:46.434
Commitment is really hard to find in...

28:46.435 --> 28:48.274
people my age.

28:48.275 --> 28:49.705
Or anybody.

28:50.645 --> 28:53.745
How can I just throw all of that away?

29:01.685 --> 29:04.974
You don't have to.

29:04.975 --> 29:07.514
And you shouldn't.

29:07.515 --> 29:08.604
We love Jareth.

29:08.605 --> 29:09.750
(quiet laugh)

29:09.751 --> 29:10.934
Uh...

29:10.935 --> 29:13.604
We just think that...

29:13.605 --> 29:16.394
if you're willing to
commit to a life together,

29:16.395 --> 29:19.644
then that's not going anywhere.

29:19.645 --> 29:23.434
It'll stand the test of time.

29:23.435 --> 29:25.739
I'm speaking in clichés now,
exclusively. I just can't...

29:25.740 --> 29:26.514
That's okay.

29:26.515 --> 29:28.514
- Dad, you're a little freaked out.
- I am.

29:28.515 --> 29:29.875
So am I. (chuckles)

29:31.315 --> 29:32.644
Okay.

29:32.645 --> 29:35.285
♪ ♪

29:37.895 --> 29:40.474
(sighs)

29:40.475 --> 29:42.014
Tell me what you know, Bess.

29:42.015 --> 29:44.934
That you made an unofficial
offer to Calvin Hastings

29:44.935 --> 29:47.434
to replace me as secretary of state.

29:47.435 --> 29:50.564
Hastings hasn't unofficially accepted.

29:50.565 --> 29:52.331
I was hoping to bring
you into the circle

29:52.332 --> 29:54.035
- when the situation...
- I've been told by

29:54.036 --> 29:55.388
Foreign Minister Avdonin

29:55.389 --> 29:56.934
that Dmitri Petrov is alive.

29:56.935 --> 29:59.934
They'll give him his freedom
in exchange for Peter Buckley.

29:59.935 --> 30:02.615
(sighs) Here we go.

30:04.895 --> 30:06.375
Give us a moment.

30:11.395 --> 30:12.394
(door opens)

30:12.395 --> 30:14.495
(door shuts)

30:19.475 --> 30:20.894
You need to let this go.

30:20.895 --> 30:22.014
Not a chance.

30:22.015 --> 30:24.814
After everything that I have done

30:24.815 --> 30:26.564
in service to you and
this administration,

30:26.565 --> 30:29.724
only to find myself turned out

30:29.725 --> 30:32.811
at the first glimmer
of political expediency?

30:32.812 --> 30:33.313
Bess...

30:33.314 --> 30:36.854
Not to mention the sacrifices
my whole family made,

30:36.855 --> 30:39.854
especially Henry, who did
his best to put it behind him

30:39.855 --> 30:41.774
and support you after his own asset

30:41.775 --> 30:43.514
was surrendered to the greater good.

30:43.515 --> 30:46.774
Do you have any idea the
stress that put on us?

30:46.775 --> 30:50.724
We survived it because we did
have a bigger picture in mind,

30:50.725 --> 30:53.514
because we did serve
at the pleasure of a man

30:53.515 --> 30:55.684
we both respected

30:55.685 --> 30:58.104
and admired and trusted.

30:58.105 --> 30:59.934
And now this? You're firing me?

30:59.935 --> 31:02.934
Bess, I'm not firing you.

31:02.935 --> 31:05.705
I'm trying to ask you
to be my vice president.

31:07.435 --> 31:08.535
Oh.

31:11.015 --> 31:12.434
What?!

31:12.435 --> 31:15.774
Mark Delgado has serious health issues.

31:15.775 --> 31:18.314
It's just not a viable
job for him anymore.

31:18.315 --> 31:19.934
It was a very short list

31:19.935 --> 31:23.724
when it came to his replacement.

31:23.725 --> 31:26.035
Only one name on it.

31:29.605 --> 31:31.934
I'm going to need your
help on the campaign trail.

31:31.935 --> 31:36.514
But more importantly, I'm
going to need your wise counsel

31:36.515 --> 31:38.644
on all matters, foreign and domestic.

31:38.645 --> 31:40.474
I didn't want to bring you into this

31:40.475 --> 31:44.974
until I had a solid choice
for secretary of state.

31:44.975 --> 31:47.785
That person has some
pretty big shoes to fill.

31:48.725 --> 31:51.724
(sighing): Uh...

31:51.725 --> 31:54.724
Mr. President...

31:54.725 --> 31:57.825
I don't know what to say.

31:59.475 --> 32:01.644
First of all, thank you.

32:01.645 --> 32:03.564
Um...

32:03.565 --> 32:05.148
And I'm sorry for the misunderstanding.

32:05.149 --> 32:07.434
It's quite all right.

32:07.435 --> 32:08.774
(trembling sigh)

32:08.775 --> 32:10.854
And then, um,

32:10.855 --> 32:14.684
I suppose I'll need some time to think.

32:14.685 --> 32:16.785
Of course.

32:24.145 --> 32:27.394
Sir, I-I'm not... I'm
not bargaining here.

32:27.395 --> 32:29.684
It's a separate issue, this
matter of Dmitri Petrov.

32:29.685 --> 32:31.509
It's out of the question.
American assets were

32:31.510 --> 32:33.684
sent to their deaths
when Buckley burned them.

32:33.685 --> 32:34.685
Two of them were friends.

32:34.686 --> 32:35.684
I know.

32:35.685 --> 32:38.283
As the former CIA director,
you know I can't begin

32:38.284 --> 32:41.242
to consider giving this
traitor his freedom.

32:41.243 --> 32:43.452
You also know that
Dmitri is probably dead.

32:43.453 --> 32:48.032
But while there's a
chance, we have to try.

32:48.033 --> 32:52.242
He was one of the most
effective assets we've ever had.

32:52.243 --> 32:54.612
His intel may have
prevented a world war.

32:54.613 --> 32:57.112
Meanwhile,

32:57.113 --> 33:01.213
Buckley is no longer a
threat to American security.

33:03.203 --> 33:06.162
But besides all that,

33:06.163 --> 33:07.612
you know in your heart of hearts

33:07.613 --> 33:08.702
that giving up Dmitri

33:08.703 --> 33:12.322
to make that deal with Russia was wrong.

33:12.323 --> 33:14.662
It was a necessary wrong.

33:14.663 --> 33:17.162
But it was wrong.

33:17.163 --> 33:20.372
Here we have a chance to make it right.

33:20.373 --> 33:22.553
How often do we get that?

33:24.703 --> 33:26.202
Here I am, offering you

33:26.203 --> 33:27.986
the second most important
job in the country,

33:27.987 --> 33:28.662
(laughs)

33:28.663 --> 33:31.492
and you're poking at my conscience.

33:31.493 --> 33:34.343
Any wonder why I want
you to take the job?

33:41.283 --> 33:44.093
Well, it looks like we both
have a lot to think about.

33:52.526 --> 33:54.525
JARETH: <i>So, for the wedding reception,</i>

33:54.526 --> 33:57.525
plenty of room for mingling
but not too cavernous.

33:57.526 --> 34:00.935
Got craft beers on tap,
nice wine selection,

34:00.936 --> 34:02.565
all the small batch liquors.

34:02.566 --> 34:04.605
Walks right up to precious,

34:04.606 --> 34:06.265
and then says, no, wait,

34:06.266 --> 34:07.706
sophisticated.

34:08.976 --> 34:10.935
Yeah.

34:10.936 --> 34:12.706
It's nice.

34:14.396 --> 34:17.225
Okay, so...

34:17.226 --> 34:18.685
why does it look like you're being

34:18.686 --> 34:19.956
led to your execution?

34:23.565 --> 34:26.725
It's, uh, it's too soon.

34:26.726 --> 34:28.264
What?

34:28.266 --> 34:29.185
For getting married.

34:29.186 --> 34:30.905
- Yes, no, I put that together.
- Jareth...

34:30.906 --> 34:32.895
I love you so much.

34:32.896 --> 34:36.576
And I love the idea of
marrying you, it's...

34:37.976 --> 34:40.815
...just every time I th... I think about

34:40.815 --> 34:43.565
actually doing it, I...

34:43.565 --> 34:46.605
I kind of feel like...

34:46.606 --> 34:48.895
throwing up or-or passing out,

34:48.896 --> 34:51.395
and-and that's not how I really

34:51.396 --> 34:52.331
want to feel.

34:52.331 --> 34:53.366
No, that's not ideal.

34:54.315 --> 34:56.025
So why can't we wait?

34:56.025 --> 34:57.685
Of course we can.

34:57.686 --> 35:00.525
It's just when I think of
being separated from you

35:00.526 --> 35:03.666
for that long without
some kind of plan...

35:04.896 --> 35:06.525
I don't want to risk it.

35:06.526 --> 35:08.685
So...

35:08.686 --> 35:09.536
let's make a plan.

35:10.646 --> 35:13.645
I will finish out my semester here

35:13.646 --> 35:16.855
and then I'll jo...
I'll join you in Oxford

35:16.856 --> 35:17.916
for the summer.

35:18.856 --> 35:20.626
We can, we can live in a...

35:22.066 --> 35:24.565
...charming little cottage and...

35:24.566 --> 35:26.645
go punting...

35:26.646 --> 35:28.149
Probably more like a sad little flat.

35:28.150 --> 35:29.395
But I do know how to punt.

35:29.396 --> 35:31.435
Well, I didn't actually
know that was a real thing,

35:31.436 --> 35:32.539
it just sounded good, so...

35:32.540 --> 35:34.640
And after our idyllic summer?

35:36.526 --> 35:40.036
We... we figure it out. Together.

35:41.726 --> 35:43.025
I like the together bit.

35:43.026 --> 35:44.866
Me, too.

35:51.436 --> 35:52.475
HENRY: <i>Babe?</i>

35:52.476 --> 35:54.025
Text from Stevie.

35:54.026 --> 35:57.645
"Wedding off, engagement
on, explain later."

35:57.646 --> 35:59.685
Oh, thank God.

35:59.686 --> 36:03.765
"P.S. summer in Oxford."

36:03.766 --> 36:06.105
Sounds expensive.

36:06.106 --> 36:07.355
(chuckles)

36:07.356 --> 36:09.645
Still, nice save, Professor.

36:09.646 --> 36:12.576
Well, believe me, she was
ready for the intervention.

36:13.976 --> 36:15.956
I need to tell you something.

36:16.896 --> 36:18.725
Couple of things, actually.

36:18.726 --> 36:20.126
Yeah?

36:22.686 --> 36:25.475
There's a chance Dmitri's still alive.

36:25.476 --> 36:27.605
What?

36:27.606 --> 36:29.065
How?

36:29.066 --> 36:30.815
I'm told the Russians preserved him

36:30.816 --> 36:33.725
in the event of a chance
for a prisoner exchange,

36:33.726 --> 36:36.525
and now that chance is here.

36:36.526 --> 36:39.395
Avdonin wants to swap
him for Peter Buckley.

36:39.396 --> 36:41.685
Took some convincing,

36:41.686 --> 36:44.145
but Conrad's agreed to the trade.

36:44.146 --> 36:45.475
He's alive.

36:45.476 --> 36:47.855
The whole thing could be a ploy.

36:47.856 --> 36:49.065
I mean, all accessible proof,

36:49.066 --> 36:51.605
everything except Avdonin's word,

36:51.606 --> 36:52.765
speaks to the contrary,

36:52.766 --> 36:56.206
and the Russians could just
be playing us to get Buckley.

36:57.816 --> 37:00.935
We wouldn't know for certain
until the actual exchange.

37:00.936 --> 37:04.145
When is it?

37:04.146 --> 37:05.475
Tomorrow night.

37:05.476 --> 37:06.765
Where?

37:06.766 --> 37:08.815
Vartius, Finland.

37:08.816 --> 37:10.956
Border checkpoint with Russia.

37:13.106 --> 37:14.895
We need someone there

37:14.896 --> 37:16.475
who can identify him.

37:16.476 --> 37:17.475
It has to be me.

37:17.476 --> 37:19.379
Do you really want to
put yourself through that?

37:19.380 --> 37:22.725
If it isn't real, what's
that gonna do to you?

37:22.726 --> 37:25.895
Y-you have to consider that, Henry.

37:25.896 --> 37:30.536
In your best ex-CIA estimation,
what are the odds he's alive?

37:32.566 --> 37:33.855
Forty-five percent.

37:33.856 --> 37:36.126
I have to go.

37:40.896 --> 37:42.666
Okay.

37:44.066 --> 37:47.036
Then we need to pack.

37:47.976 --> 37:49.895
What was the other thing?

37:49.896 --> 37:52.895
Oh...

37:52.896 --> 37:55.475
Conrad asked me to
be his Vice President.

37:55.476 --> 37:56.935
Oh... what?

37:56.936 --> 38:00.565
ELIZABETH: Yeah, big day.

38:00.566 --> 38:01.705
MATT: <i>Uh, good morning.</i>

38:01.706 --> 38:02.537
(feedback whines)

38:02.538 --> 38:04.161
- MAN: Good morning.
- I'd like to, uh...

38:04.162 --> 38:06.605
(stammers)

38:06.606 --> 38:10.036
uh, begin by stating the obvious.

38:11.106 --> 38:15.706
I am not Elizabeth McCord.

38:17.936 --> 38:20.536
I'm her speechwriter.

38:21.936 --> 38:24.855
Believe me, uh, no one
is more disappointed that

38:24.856 --> 38:26.855
the secretary won't
be giving the address

38:26.856 --> 38:28.565
that I wrote for her.

38:28.566 --> 38:29.855
You know, now that I know

38:29.856 --> 38:31.399
that it'll never see the light of day,

38:31.400 --> 38:33.935
I think it's safe to say that

38:33.936 --> 38:35.645
it was the greatest speech ever written.

38:35.646 --> 38:37.645
(audience laughs)

38:37.646 --> 38:39.855
I mean, honestly, uh,

38:39.856 --> 38:43.265
this is probably the first
moment in my adult life

38:43.266 --> 38:45.996
that I've stood in the spotlight.

38:47.266 --> 38:50.666
Truth be told, it's
probably gonna be the last.

38:51.856 --> 38:54.145
Why?

38:54.146 --> 38:58.025
Because I'm one of those
people who works in the dark.

38:58.026 --> 39:00.025
I know what you're thinking.

39:00.026 --> 39:04.025
As soon as my Etsy
page is discovered, uh,

39:04.026 --> 39:07.525
I'll invent my own job title
on Buzzfeed and livestream

39:07.526 --> 39:09.935
my Christopher Walken
impression as I hoverboard

39:09.936 --> 39:11.975
to the Soylent dispenser
in the playroom...

39:11.976 --> 39:13.935
(audience laughs)

39:13.936 --> 39:15.225
...and I don't blame you.

39:15.226 --> 39:20.605
In this world of
relentless self-promotion,

39:20.606 --> 39:23.935
we've all been raised to
think that the limelight

39:23.936 --> 39:26.326
is the only light worth seeking.

39:28.266 --> 39:30.286
But that isn't the case.

39:33.106 --> 39:36.605
And if I can impart one thing today,

39:36.606 --> 39:41.025
a small, simple truth to carry with you

39:41.026 --> 39:44.126
as you walk through
those gates, it's this:

39:46.766 --> 39:50.206
<i>Achievement is often anonymous.</i>

39:53.186 --> 39:54.935
<i>Some of the greatest things</i>

39:54.936 --> 39:58.666
<i>have been done by people
you have never heard of...</i>

40:00.726 --> 40:04.706
<i>...quietly dedicating their
lives to improving your own.</i>

40:34.266 --> 40:36.366
♪ ♪

40:58.896 --> 41:00.366
(men speaking Russian)

41:11.026 --> 41:12.126
(speaking Russian)

41:16.726 --> 41:19.206
(speaking Russian)

41:22.816 --> 41:23.685
It's him.

41:23.686 --> 41:25.685
That's a positive identification, sir?

41:25.686 --> 41:27.246
Yes, it's him.

41:55.436 --> 41:56.746
(spits)

